Ogun State Government on Wednesday, gave conditional approval for the reopening of religious worship centres across the state from August 14, 2020 with a warning that congregants must strictly adhere to the rules stipulated in the COVID-19 protocols. The government also approved August 4th, 2020 as schools’ resumption date for students preparing to sit for the regional terminal examination organised by the West African Examination Council (WAEC). The state governor, Prince Dapo Abiodun, who addressed journalists yesterday in Abeokuta, the state capital said his administration resolved to lifting the ban on gathering for religious purposes and schools after due consultations with critical stakeholders, particularly the League of Imams and Alfas as well as the leadership of the Christian Association of Nigeria (CAN) as it affects churches and mosques. He explained that his administration has continued to engage different stakeholders in the educational sector “and we have received far-reaching recommendations”. “In line with the federal government resolutions, exit classes, that is – strictly SS3 only (public or private schools) – will resume classes on Tuesday, 4th August, 2020.